istent intellectual stimulus (more so than was the case with most general women's clubs) and because women discovered a world of possibilities, both public and private, inspired by their reading of Shakespeare. Indeed, gathering to read and discuss Shakespeare often led women to actively improve their lot in life and make their society a better place. Many clubs took action on larger social issues such as women's suffrage, philanthropy, and civil rights. At the same time, these efforts served to embed Shakespeare into American culture as a marker for learning, self-improvement, civilization, and entertainment for a broad array of populations, varying in age, race, location, and social standing.Based on extensive research in the archives of the Folger Shakespeare Library and in dozens of local archives and private collections across America, She Hath Been Reading shows the important role that literature can play in the lives of ordinary people. As testament to this fact, the book includes an appendix listing more than five hundred Shakespeare clubs across America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBook clubs (Discussion groups)xHistoryxUnited States. 0aBook clubs (Discussion groups)zUnited StatesxHistory. 0aWomenxBooks and readingxHistoryxUnited States. 0aWomenxBooks and readingzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aWomenxIntellectual lifexUnited States. 0aWomenxSocieties and clubsxHistoryxUnited States. 0aWomenzUnited StatesxIntellectual life. 0aWomenzUnited StatesxSocieties and clubsxHistory. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPerforming Arts & Drama. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Shakespeare.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146422540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801464225423Coveruhttps